FROM the origin of Tragedy, to the days of Theſpis, and from his time to that of Aeſchylus, all is doubt, conjecture and obſcurity;
neither Ariſtotle, nor any other antient writer, give us the leaſt inſight into the ſtate and progreſs of the Greek drama: if his treatiſe call'd This treatiſe contain'd an exact account of the names, times, and authors of all the plays that were ever acted.
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 had reach'd poſterity, it would probably have afforded us much pleaſure and inſtruction: the names of a few, and but a few tragedians, during this dark period, are handed down to us: ſuch were The Bacchae, a tragedy of his, is cited by Athenaeus. Epigenes, the Sicyonian, and Pratinas, who wrote fifty plays, thirty-two of which are ſaid to have been ſatyrical: after Theſpis, came his ſcholar Phrynicus, who wrote nine tragedies, for See Strabo, Herodotus and Plutarch. one of which we are told he was fined fifty drachmas, becauſe he had made it (an odd reaſon) too deep, and too affecting: there was alſo another Phrynicus, author of Call'd, Andromeda and Erigone. two tragedies; to theſe we muſt add Mention'd by Macrobius and Pollux. Alcaeus, Phormus, and Choerilus is ſaid to have written no leſs than a hundred and twenty tragedies. Choerilus; together with Cephiſodorus, an Athenian, who wrote the Amazons, and Apollophanes, ſuppoſed to have been the author of a tragedy, named Daulis; though Suidas is of another opinion.
